Concurrency.

Concurrency is the number of execution environments running your function at the same time. The account has a regional limit, defaulting to a thousand, shared across every function that hasn't reserved any.

Reserved concurrency is pinned to one function. It both guarantees that function always has at least that capacity, so nothing else can starve it, and caps it at that limit. A common use is protecting a downstream resource: if a database handles fifty connections, you cap the function at fifty.

Provisioned concurrency is a different lever: it pre-warms a set number of environments so their requests have no cold start, and you pay for that count regardless of traffic, so it's for latency-sensitive ay-pee-eyes, not for throughput. When a function exceeds its limit, Lambda throttles: synchronous callers get an immediate too-many-requests error, asynchronous events are queued and retried, and pollers back off.
